    q(6,"What is the inverse of the 2x2 identity matrix?",["The zero matrix","Itself (the identity matrix)","Does not exist","[[0,1],[1,0]]"],"I*I = I, so I^(-1) = I.",1),
    q(7,"For a 3x3 matrix, the augmented matrix [A|I] has dimensions:",["3x3","3x6","6x3","6x6"],"A is 3x3 and I is 3x3, so [A|I] is 3x6.",1),
    q(8,"If row reduction of [A|I] yields [[1,0,0|2,-1,0],[0,1,0|-3,2,1],[0,0,1|1,0,-1]], what is A^(-1)?",["[[2,-1,0],[-3,2,1],[1,0,-1]]","[[1,0,0],[0,1,0],[0,0,1]]","Cannot be determined","The transpose of the left side"],"The right side after complete reduction gives A^(-1) = [[2,-1,0],[-3,2,1],[1,0,-1]].",0),
    q(9,"Can you find the inverse of a non-square matrix using row reduction?",["Yes, for any matrix","Only for tall matrices","Only for wide matrices","No, inverses only exist for square matrices"],"Matrix inverses (two-sided) are defined only for square matrices. Non-square matrices may have left or right inverses but not a full inverse.",3),
    q(10,"What is the computational cost of finding an inverse via row reduction for an nxn matrix?",["O(n^2)","O(n^3)","O(n^4)","O(2^n)"],"Row reducing [A|I] to [I|A^(-1)] requires roughly 2n^3/3 + n^3 = O(n^3) operations, similar to solving n systems.",1),
    q(11,"What does 'augmenting with the identity' mean?",["Placing the identity matrix to the right of A to form [A|I]","Adding I to A","Multiplying A by I","Replacing A with I"],"Augmenting with the identity means writing A and I side by side: [A | I]. Row operations on this matrix simultaneously transform both A and I.",0),
    q(12,"What does 'elementary row operations preserve invertibility' mean?",["Row operations cannot change whether a matrix is invertible","Row operations always make a matrix invertible","Row operations can only be applied to invertible matrices","Row operations convert invertible matrices to singular ones"],"Elementary row operations are themselves invertible operations (each can be undone). They do not change whether the original matrix A is invertible or not.",0),
    q(13,"What is a 'row reduction algorithm' for finding inverses?",["A systematic process of applying row operations to [A|I] until the left side becomes I, at which point the right side is A^(-1)","Random row swaps until the identity appears","Computing the determinant first, then dividing","Multiplying A by random matrices"],"The algorithm applies forward elimination and back elimination (Gauss-Jordan) to [A|I], transforming the left side to I and the right side to A^(-1).",0),
    q(14,"What does 'pivot position' tell you about invertibility during row reduction?",["If every column has a pivot, the matrix is invertible","If any column lacks a pivot, the matrix is invertible","Pivots are unrelated to invertibility","Only the first pivot matters"],"During row reduction, if every column of A contains a pivot (full rank), A is invertible. If any column lacks a pivot, A is singular.",0),
    q(15,"What does 'RREF of [A|I]' give?",["[I|A^(-1)] if A is invertible, or a matrix with a zero row on the left if A is singular","Always the identity","Always [A|A]","The determinant"],"If A is invertible, RREF of [A|I] = [I|A^(-1)]. If A is singular, a zero row appears on the left side.",0),
    q(16,"What does 'checking the inverse' mean?",["Verifying that A*A^(-1) = I and A^(-1)*A = I","Checking that det(A^(-1)) = 1","Ensuring A^(-1) has no zeros","Computing the trace of A^(-1)"],"After computing A^(-1), multiply A*A^(-1) and verify it equals I. This catches arithmetic errors.",0),
    q(17,"What is the 'Gauss-Jordan method' for inverses?",["Using both forward and backward elimination on [A|I] to reach [I|A^(-1)]","Using only forward elimination","Computing cofactors","Finding eigenvalues"],"Gauss-Jordan applies forward elimination (zeros below pivots) and backward elimination (zeros above pivots) plus pivot scaling to transform A into I.",0),
    q(18,"What does 'ill-conditioned matrix' mean for inverse computation?",["The matrix is rectangular","The inverse exists but is very sensitive to rounding errors","The matrix has no inverse","The matrix is diagonal"],"An ill-conditioned matrix has a large condition number. Its inverse exists but is numerically unreliable due to amplification of rounding errors.",1),
    q(19,"What is 'partial pivoting' used for in inverse computation?",["Improving numerical stability by swapping rows to place the largest entry in the pivot position","Making computation faster","Reducing memory usage","Ensuring the inverse is symmetric"],"Partial pivoting selects the largest absolute value in the pivot column, reducing numerical errors during row reduction.",0),
    q(20,"What is the relationship between row reducing A to I and expressing I as a product of elementary matrices times A?",["Each row operation corresponds to left-multiplication by an elementary matrix, so I = E_k...E_2*E_1*A, meaning A^(-1) = E_k...E_1","They are unrelated","Row reduction is division","Elementary matrices are only theoretical"],"Row reduction of A to I means E_k...E_1*A = I, so A^(-1) = E_k...E_1. The same operations applied to I give A^(-1).",0),
    q(21,"A pharmacist needs to solve Ax = b1, Ax = b2, and Ax = b3 for the same 3x3 matrix A. She decides to compute A^(-1) first. Is this efficient?",["Yes, computing A^(-1) once allows quick solutions for all three right-hand sides","No, she should use Gaussian elimination three separate times","Only if A is diagonal","Only if all b vectors are the same"],"Computing A^(-1) once costs O(n^3). Then each x = A^(-1)*b costs O(n^2). For multiple right-hand sides, this is more efficient than repeating full elimination.",0),
    q(22,"An electrical engineer row-reduces [[1,-1|1,0],[2,3|0,1]]. After R2-2R1: [[1,-1|1,0],[0,5|-2,1]]. After R2/5 and R1+R2: what is A^(-1)?",["[[3/5,1/5],[-2/5,1/5]]","[[3,1],[-2,1]]","[[0.6,0.2],[-0.4,0.2]]","Both A and C"],"R2/5: [[1,-1|1,0],[0,1|-2/5,1/5]]. R1+R2: [[1,0|3/5,1/5],[0,1|-2/5,1/5]]. A^(-1)=[[3/5,1/5],[-2/5,1/5]] = [[0.6,0.2],[-0.4,0.2]].",3),
    q(23,"A data scientist row-reduces a 100x100 matrix [A|I] and finds a zero row on the left at row 73. What should she conclude?",["A is invertible with a special structure","A is singular and has no inverse","She made a computational error","The inverse is a 73x73 matrix"],"A zero row on the left during reduction means A does not have full rank and is singular. No inverse exists.",1),
    q(24,"A control systems engineer needs A^(-1) for a 4x4 matrix. She uses software that reports 'matrix is singular or nearly singular.' What should she do?",["Force the computation anyway","Check the condition number and consider regularization or an alternative formulation","Conclude that no solution exists to Ax=b","Increase the matrix size"],"A singularity warning means either the matrix is exactly singular or very ill-conditioned. She should check the condition number and consider alternatives.",1),
    q(25,"A navigation engineer has matrix A = [[1,0,1],[0,1,1],[1,1,0]]. She augments with I and row reduces. After elimination, the left side becomes I. She reads A^(-1) from the right. Verify: is det(A) nonzero?",["Yes, det = -2","No, det = 0","Yes, det = 2","Yes, det = 1"],"det = 1(0-1) - 0 + 1(0-1) = -1 - 1 = -2. Since det != 0, A is invertible.",0),
    q(26,"A biologist models population dynamics with P = [[0.8,0.3],[0.2,0.7]]. She computes P^(-1) to reverse-forecast past populations. Is P invertible?",["Yes, det = 0.56-0.06 = 0.50 != 0","No, population matrices are never invertible","Yes, det = 1","Cannot determine"],"det = 0.8(0.7) - 0.3(0.2) = 0.56 - 0.06 = 0.50 != 0. P is invertible.",0),
